e regenerated by the workflow, right? Typically, agents add their tests, and then the metadata generator updates things. The current repo has metadata 1.48 from a previous run, but we won't touch that. However, if we add a new serialization test, it might need extra metadata beyond what’s checked, which could lead to a failure in the native run if it's not regenerated. In this case, metadata will be generated externally.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating metadata generation**\\n\\nI’m looking at whether the PR needs metadata, but the rule says not to edit. I'm considering if a new test could generate broad serialization metadata for AppEngineCredentials with test-specific implementations. This serialization only covers AppEngineCredentials, not the transient test references. There’s also potential to produce more metadata that might not be necessary, especially if there’s no reporter involved. I’m weighing whether the test addresses the readObject dynamic reflection correctly, which seems likely. Overall, it’s important to finalize this concisely!\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Updated `tests/src/com.google.auth/google-auth-library-oauth2-http/1.48.0/src/test/java/com_google_auth/google_auth_library_oauth2_http/AppEngineCredentialsTest.java`.\n\nWhat changed:\n- Added an App Engine credentials serialization/deserialization test.\n- The new test exercises the public `GoogleCredentials.getApplicationDefault()` and Java serialization path.\n- It verifies that deserialized App Engine credentials reinitialize the App Identity service and can still:\n  - sign data through `ServiceAccountSigner`\n  - refresh an access token through the public credentials API\n\nNo `build.gradle` changes were needed, and I did not edit reachability metadata or native-image config files. Tests were not run, per instruction.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0be1d0f9a90ef3cf016a2a96c2a23c819592c7015223462aa1\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-respo